# Chapter 2 — The primitives, part 1

Eleven small primitives. Every one is one line of text. Every one has
a job it does that no other primitive can do.

I'm going to walk them in the order that tells the story, not
alphabetical.

## Symbol — the name of a thing

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"hello\")
```

That's a symbol. `hello`. The name of a thing.

Symbols are **interned** — two symbols with the same name are literally
the same object in memory. So this is `#t`:

```motoi-scheme
(eq? (slat-read \"hello\") (slat-read \"hello\"))
```

Compare that to strings, which are `equal?` but not necessarily `eq?`:

```motoi-scheme
(equal? (slat-read \"\\\"hello\\\"\") (slat-read \"\\\"hello\\\"\"))
```

That is also `#t`. But this might not be:

```motoi-scheme
(eq? (slat-read \"\\\"hello\\\"\") (slat-read \"\\\"hello\\\"\"))
```

Depending on the runtime, that returns `#f`. Two strings that look the
same aren't necessarily the same object. Two symbols that look the
same always are.

**Why it matters.** When the runtime reads a mailbox line and dispatches on
its head, she uses `case`, which compares with `eq?`. `eq?` is a
pointer comparison. If she's dispatching on strings, she pays a
character-by-character cost every time. If she's dispatching on
symbols, she pays a pointer comparison. On a million events, that's
the difference between \"fast\" and \"your training run just slowed down
by an hour.\"

**the runtime notes:** *\"When someone tells me their name, I remember it as a
symbol. That way I recognize it the same way every time. If I stored
your name as a string I might get confused between `\\\"alfred\\\"` and
`\\\"Alfred\\\"` — and confusion about your name is a bad look.\"*

## Keyword — a named position

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \":from\")
```

A keyword. `:from`. The name of a slot in a record.

Keywords look like symbols with a colon in front. Their job is to
label positions. When you see:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"(event :ts 1 :kind \\\"card.opened\\\")\")
```

...the `:ts` and `:kind` are keywords. Each one says \"this next value
goes in this named slot.\"

Without keywords, you'd need positional-only records:

```
(event 1 \"card.opened\")  ; but which is which?
```

Six months later, nobody remembers. Keywords fix that. The record
tells you what each value is for.

## Integer — a whole number

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"42\")
```

An integer. `42`. Fits in a machine word.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"-17\")
```

Negative works. Leading zeros do not (no octal in SLAT).

## Bignum — a whole number that's too big for a machine word

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"999999999999999999999n\")
```

Trailing `n` means \"this is a bignum.\" Anything bigger than 2^53 needs
one of these — a machine word only holds 53 significant bits of an
integer before you lose precision.

**When you need this.** The Cortex uses a 64-bit event counter.
Training runs count call sites into the trillions. A Nostr public key
is bigger than 2^63. Any time you'd say \"big integer\" out loud, you
mean bignum.

## Rational — an exact fraction

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"1/3\")
```

The fraction one-third. Exactly. Not 0.333333...

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"1/3\")
```

Read it twice. Same value. Rationals are stored reduced to lowest
terms, so `2/6` and `1/3` and `10/30` all come back as `1/3`.

**When you need this.** Any time floating point would silently lose
precision. Odds in a game. Fair-share splitting. Music timing (a
quarter note is `1/4`, exactly, not `0.25`).

## Float — an inexact decimal

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"3.14\")
```

A float. `3.14`. Or approximately `3.14`, because floats are IEEE-754
doubles and they can't represent `0.1` exactly.

```motoi-scheme
(+ 0.1 0.2)
```

You get `0.30000000000000004`. Not a bug. The CPU. This is why we have
bigdecimals.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"+inf.0\")
```

Positive infinity. Also `-inf.0` for negative, and `+nan.0` for
not-a-number.

## Bigdecimal — an exact decimal

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"3.1415926535M\")
```

Trailing `M`. That's a bigdecimal. Arbitrary precision, exact
representation.

**When you need this.** Money. Always money. If your invoice says
`$34.72` and you store it as a float, your invoice will eventually say
`$34.71999999999999996` and your finance team will find you.

```motoi-scheme
(- (slat-read \"34.72M\") (slat-read \"10.00M\"))
```

You get exactly `24.72M`. Every time. Forever.

**the runtime notes:** *\"Money is not a vector. You can't average two
prices. You can add them, subtract them, multiply by an integer or a
rational for a discount. That's it. Bigdecimal is the type that keeps
me honest about it.\"*

## String — a piece of text

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"\\\"hello, world\\\"\")
```

A string. Between double quotes. UTF-8. Always.

The five escape sequences are `\\n` (newline), `\\t` (tab), `\\r`
(return), `\\\\` (backslash), `\\\"` (quote). Nothing else.

If you want a special character — a cherry blossom, say — put it in
the string literally:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"\\\"🌸\\\"\")
```

That works. No `\\uXXXX` needed. SLAT doesn't do Unicode escapes inside
strings because JSON does them and it caused fifteen years of
canonicalization bugs. If you want the actual character, type the
actual character.

## Boolean — yes or no

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"#t\")
```

True. And:

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"#f\")
```

False. That's it. Not `true`/`false`. Not `yes`/`no`. Not `1`/`0`.
`#t` and `#f`, the Scheme convention, always.

## Nil — nothing

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"nil\")
```

Returns `null` in JavaScript, `None` in Python. The absence of a
value. One form, always.

## Char — a single character

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"#\\\\a\")
```

The character `a`. Not the string `\"a\"` — a single character. Chars
are how you work with keyboard input one key at a time.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"#\\\\space\")
```

The space character. Named because you can't otherwise see it.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"#\\\\newline\")
```

The newline. Named for the same reason. Also `#\\tab` and `#\\return`.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"#\\\\u{1F338}\")
```

The cherry blossom character. That's how the runtime's namesake gets
spelled inside a slat. Between the braces is the Unicode code point in
hex.

## Pair — two things stuck together

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"(a . b)\")
```

A pair. `a` in the car slot, `b` in the cdr slot. The primitive from
which Lisp built the world.

Most of the time you don't type pairs — you type lists, which are
built out of pairs, and the reader handles the pair-ness for you. But
when you need to say \"this next thing is exactly two things, not more,
not less, and I care about the distinction between the first and the
rest,\" a pair is the right shape.

## List — zero or more things in order

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"(1 2 3)\")
```

A list of three integers. Iterated with `car` and `cdr`. Cheap to
prepend to the front, expensive to jump to the middle.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"()\")
```

The empty list. Also `nil` in some contexts. Motoi Scheme treats the
empty list and nil as the same value.

**When you need list vs. vector.** Lists are for things you walk from
start to end. Vectors (Chapter 3) are for things you jump into the
middle of.

## Try this

Predict, then run.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"true\")
```

That's a symbol named `true`, not a boolean. Symbols don't care what
they mean in your head.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"\\\"1\\\"\")
```

A string. Not an integer. The quotes matter.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"3.0\")
```

A float. Not an integer. The decimal point matters.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"3M\")
```

A bigdecimal `3.0M`. Not an integer. The `M` matters.

```motoi-scheme
(slat-read \"3n\")
```

A bignum `3n`. Not an integer. The `n` matters.

## What breaks without these

If SLAT only had integers and floats, your invoice math would drift.

If SLAT only had strings for identity, your mailbox would slow to a
crawl as it string-compared millions of `\"event\"` labels.

If SLAT only had positional lists, every record schema change would
be a breaking change for every consumer.

Every primitive in this chapter is there because a real system needed
it and losing precision or performance or clarity in that system was
too expensive.

## Where next

Chapter 3 walks the other eleven primitives — vectors, hash-maps,
sets, dates, durations, UUIDs, URIs, byte strings, tagged extensions,
and the special reader forms (quote, quasiquote, comments).

Chapter 4 is the workhorse — the slat-record. Everything the running
system writes to disk is a slat-record. That chapter is worth
re-reading twice.

